<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the Law Centres Network (LAI 0055)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Introduction</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">The Law Centres Network is the membership body for Law Centres in England, Wales and Northern Ireland, each of which is a not-for-profit legal practice providing legal </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">services</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> in civil law, with a particular focus on social welfare law. There are over 50 Law Centres across the UK represented in the Network, all but 2 of which hold legal aid contracts. Law Centres have practiced in these areas of law since their inception in 197</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">0, and the Law Centres Network (trading name of the Law Centres Federation) has coordinated and represented them collectively since 1978. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Overarching C</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">oncerns</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">The Law Centres Network’s overriding concern is that the Ministry of Justice proposals to ‘tra</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">nsform’ legal aid would significantly limit access to justice for many of our clients. As the cuts – such as they are – affect </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">disadvantaged</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> groups </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">more</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">, we believe they run counter to the fundamental principle of equality before the law. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">The Ministry of J</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ustice admits “the potential for disproportionate impacts on some persons with protected characteristics”</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">but still</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> considers the cuts</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> justified. We believe that </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">these</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> disproportionate impact</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">on, for example, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">women and BAME groups</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">, should not be </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">discounted. The withdrawal of effective remedy will hit people of modest means hard and vulnerable people harder. It would seem that, despite the Justice Secretary’s claim, effective access to justice and equality of arms at court do depend on an individua</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">l’s ability to pay.</span></li><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">While government’s need to manage down the cost of legal aid is understandable, the proposals it is making in pursuit of this aim reflect a jaundiced view of citizens’ right to hold the state to account by challenging the actions and de</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">cisions of public bodies. We regard the proposals as contrary to the pr</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">inciples of the rule of law and </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">accountable public administration. Their adoption would send out a dangerous message that public bodies can in effect act unlawfully with impunity.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">One</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> likely outcome of government’s proposals would be market failure, affecting both clients and providers. Cuts are likely to create shortages of expertise in areas, such as public law or prison law, which would widen the gulf between demand and supply of le</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">gal services – especially ones targeted at disadvantaged and vulnerable people. Ironically, the proposed cuts are aimed at strengthening public confidence in the legal aid system; we cannot see how such gaping holes in provision </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">and loss of expertise over </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">time </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">would inspire public confidence. This additional obstacle to access to justice was not accounted for in the Ministry of Justice impact assessments.</span></li><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">More broadly, government’s assessments of the likely impact of these cuts were deeply flawed. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">The Ministry of Justice conducted its impact assessments under the assumptions that supply will meet demand and that quality (of legal services) will not suffer even as fees are reduced. Given some of the phenomena already familiar in public contracting, s</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">uch as </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">cherry-picking</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">paralegalisation</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> (work performed by more junior staff due to cost considerations) both assumptions seem far-fetched and so might skew the impact assessment to understate the cuts’ adverse impact on access to justice. </span></li><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Crucially, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">the impact assessments </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">are inadequate because they consider</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> the current proposals in isolation. A fuller </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">and more illuminating examination would position current proposals</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> against </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">the immediate backdrop of other recent cuts, such as the 10% civi</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">l legal aid fee reduction of October 2011 and the scope, eligibility and other changes imposed from April 2013 in implementing the Legal Aid Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> (LASPO)</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> Act 2012. These recent changes make it difficult to assess even what</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> the baseline position looks like</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">, especially as more proposals and consultations appear in rapid succession</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">This in turn makes it difficult for government to assess the impact of their current proposals on access to justice and casts doubt over their sav</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ings projections</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Finally,</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">the cuts </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">proposals </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">are intended to be approved by p</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">arliament as secondary legislation. This means that some substantial</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">, constitutional</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> changes to the British justice system will be enacted </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">almost by stealth, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">no debate and </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">h</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ardly any parliamentary scrutiny. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">We believe that parliament should not allow this to happen.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">              </span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Residence Test </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">The Ministry of Justice considers the ‘particular disadvantage’ the residence test would cause non-UK nationals as ‘justified’ and ‘proportionate’; we disagree. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">We believe that the residency requirement proposal is unjust because it runs contrary to the pr</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">inciple of equality before the law, creating one law for Britons and another for migrants and denying non-UK nationals the right to equal access to the courts and the right to a fair trial. The proposal would make migrants in the UK particularly susceptibl</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">e to arbitrary decisions and other abuses of power, as they would be denied help to stand up for their lawful rights. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">We think that the residence test is also unlawful because it will discriminate against non-UK nationals as a group, thus contravening the </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Human Rights Act 1998 as giving force to the European Convention on Human Rights, in particular Articles 14, 16 and 1. We also believe that the proposal, if enacted, will be in breach of Article 21(2) (non-discrimination on grounds of nationality) and Arti</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">cle 47 (right to an effective remedy and to a fair trial) of the Charter of Fundamental Rights of the European Union, as well as Council Directive 2002/8/EC and the UK’s own Equality Act 2010 (in particular section 29). </span></li><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">The proposal would also unjustly an</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">d disproportionately affect</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> the most vulnerable in society</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">particularly women, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">slipping under the safety net of legal aid because of the residence test</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Disadvantaged and vulnerable people</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> are not only the groups at which legal aid is generally aimed; the</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">y are also the ones in </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">the greatest need of the protection and remedy of the law: victims of domestic violence, trafficking or forced marriages; children, in particular separated migrant children; new refugees or failed asylum seekers who cannot be deporte</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">d; people with mental health problems, and others. Other impecunious people demanding justice in English courts – for example, the bereaved family of Jean Charles de Menezes – would also be excluded by the proposal. By the nature of their circumstances, it</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> will be very difficult to evidence the required residence of children, homeless people, and certain people with mental illness. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Southwark Law Centre, for example,</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> took on the case of a man who was brought to the UK as a child and only found out when he re</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ached adulthood that his status had never been normalised. He was unable to continue working and was forced to depend on the mother of his children, which in part led to their relationship breaking down, leaving him homeless. The Law Centre helped him gain</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> asylum and be awarded asylum support, solving </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">his immigration status and</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> his homelessness</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> and enabling him to be an active parent to his children</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> – but neither would have been possible if a residence test had been imposed.</span></li><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">The proposed residence</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">test </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">risks excluding</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> rightful UK citizens. I</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">t is hard to see how people fleeing tormentors or destitute people, or indeed people who have never had a passport, would be able to produce required documentation. Britons returning from life abroad, in particular ba</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">bies less than a year old, British children born abroad or newly arrived wives suffering domestic abuse – all would be excluded outright. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">However, sometimes the adverse eff</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ect of the residence test is not that obvious. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Birmingham Law Centre</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">took on the cas</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">e of non-EU citizen who was </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> primar</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">y carer of her daughter,</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> an EU citizen. The mother</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> was refused </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">benefits and was at risk of having to leave the country</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> with</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> her daugh</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">er</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">and thereby the daughter would have lost the substance of her</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> EU rights. As the c</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">hild, who is</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> an EU citizen, could not be a party to proceedings this case could only be pursued on behalf of the mother, who is not an EU citizen and therefore would have been refused legal aid for challenging the benefits decision – thereby adversely impa</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">cting her daughter’s rights.</span></li><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Even following the government response to the ‘Transforming Legal Aid’ consultation, there are still significant uncertainties as to how the residence test would apply</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> in practice</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">; why the qualifying period was set at twelve mo</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">nths; or</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">, importantly,</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> what evidence might satisfy the requirement. If adopted, we fear the proposal will put legal aid lawyers in the position of immigration officers, which they neither seek nor are equipped to undertake. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">The financial implications of mistaken assessments of evidence of a year’s lawful residence are potentially significant, and this is likely to push legal aid providers to err on the side of caution, thereby risking denial of legal aid to eligible people. T</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">hese uncertainties will simply </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">increase the adverse effects of the residence test as an obstacle to ordinary people’s access to justice.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">              </span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; padding-bottom:1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Judicial Review</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">The Law Centres Network has grave concerns </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">that p</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">roposal</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">s to curtail legal aid for Judicial Review would lead to a chilling effect that would create an effective obstacle to access to justice. Judicial Review is a powerful but complex tool, and it would not be reasonable to expect most members of the public to </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">undertake it without legal advice. However, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">he wa</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">y that lawyers handle Judicial Review will change</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> as the risk of no remuneration at all would increase significantly</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> – and this is especially </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">problematic for</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> not-for-profit organisations such as Law Centres</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">. With </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">so </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">much work done before permission is granted and greatly increased uncertainty as to whether it will be paid for, many providers will be put off pursuing cases even if they have moderately good prospects of succeeding, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">a scenario becoming more lik</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ely with more complex cases that would require more preparatory work. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">The obstruction that Judicial Review proposals pose to access to justice is obvious. In December 2012 </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Sheffield Law Centre took on the case of a group of parents wising to challenge the city council’s decision to cut funding for 20 nurseries, located in the most deprived areas of the city, where it is not viable to run a commercial nursery. After being rej</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ected on papers in May the case was granted permission in an oral hearing in June, with the judge reasoning that in refusing permission ‘there could be a real risk of causing real injustice’. Under Ministry of Justice proposals, seven months of preparatory</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> work would have been undertaken at the expense of the Law Centre, which means that the Law Centre would have been highly unlikely to take up the case in the first place, simply for lack of means</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">. The concerned parents would have been left facing ‘real inj</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ustice’. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Another problem posed by Judicial Review proposals is that they would likely lead to unintended adverse consequences. The risk of financial </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">liability to</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> small firms or not-for-profits such as Law </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Centres would have them be overly cautious, turni</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ng away stronger cases along with ones of </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">lesser</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> merit. The same reason would also </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">create a perverse incentive </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">for lawyers </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">to litigate in a more uncompromising manner, seeking permission </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">first ahead of trying to settle a case</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">his ‘hardball’ approach </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">is u</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">nhelpful to resolving disputes. It also </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">invariably </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">privileges</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> the party </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">of greater means:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> normally the public body concerned, not the citizen. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">This inequality</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> of arms at court flies in the face of equality before the law. </span></li><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">modest </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">projected cost savings</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> of £1m per year for Judicial Review changes do not add up when weighed against citizens’ </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">access to justice. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Southwark Law Centre </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">represented</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> a severely disabled single man suffering with MS and diabetes, living with his elderly mother who was unable to ca</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">re for him. Instead of using social services or external carers, Mr B relocated to a different local authority to be cared for by his sisters, but there he was assessed at the lowest housing priority despite meeting criteria for the highest priority. The L</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">aw Centre helped bring a Judicial Review against the council to get them to reconsider, which did and the case w</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">as settled by consent. Under</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> M</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">inistry of Justice </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">proposals the Law Centre’s work on getting the man housed and cared for </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">– </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">thus </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">saving down</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">stream costs for the state</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> and grief for him</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> – </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">would not have been </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">funded</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> by legal aid</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> because it settled before permission stage. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Thus, the Law Centre </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">would not have had alternative</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> means for pursuing justice</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> for</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> the client, and he would </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">have </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">be</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">en</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> left without effective remedy.</span></li><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">As the above indicates, we are concerned that if Ministry of Justice proposals are implemented Judicial Review would not be available to the vast majority of people, meaning that they would not be able to hold public bodies </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">to account. From families facing homelessness unable to challenge local authority decisions not to house them to victims of state violence, the proposal will mean they will no longer have recourse to legal remedies. This would contravene their rights under</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> Article 6 of the European Convention on Human Rights and Article 47 of the European Union Charter of Fundamental Rights. Removal of the ability to challenge public bodies will also mean significantly reduced public scrutiny of them. The pr</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">oposed curtailme</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">nt of Judicial R</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">eview will send out a clear message to public bodies that they can bend and break rules with impunity – compromising the rule of law.</span></li><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">There is still no indication of the guidelines that the Legal Aid Agency might have for awarding legal aid</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> to Judicial Review cases concluding before permission stage. In itself, this vague gesture toward a concession would not be enough to reassure practitioners to take the risk. In fact, if such interim gestures at ‘safety valve’ measures are indicative, rec</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ent experience is not encouraging. The exceptional funding mechanism outlined in section 10 of the LASPO Act 2012 </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">seems a reasonable example of such a ‘safety valve’; however, in practice it </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">has </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">translated into a significant hurdle of a 14-page application</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> form, up to three weeks’ waiting time for an LAA </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">funding </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">decision, and so far only 20 exceptional cases funded since April 2013</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">, compared with</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> 5,000-7,000 originally forecast by the Ministry of Justice.</span></li><div style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; clear:both; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"></div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 5.25pt; padding-bottom:10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">              </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 5.25pt; padding-bottom:1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Borderline cases</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">              </span></p></ol><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> proposal </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">to no longer award legal aid to ‘borderline’ cases </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> disproportionate to the problem it ostensibly aims to solve, not least because the Ministry of Justice has so far accepted that those cases are often high-priority cases. ‘Borderline’ cases that are awa</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">rded legal aid are fairly rare, but they are of overwhe</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">lming importance to the client, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">concerning as they do life, home and other basic human rights</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">. They are also</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> of considerable import to developing case law and clarifying </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">points of law (hence the diffic</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ulty in assessing their prospects), benefiting justice more broadly.</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Cutting </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">borderline</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> cases will be to</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> the detriment of clients, for example, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">cases involving children, or </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">County Court possession cases where imminent homelessness is at stake. Owin</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">g to their great importance </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">of ‘borderline’ cases </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">to clients, the</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ir</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> continued funding is </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">integral to preserving people’s </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">access to just</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ice in extreme cases – and we believe it outweighs the modest saving of £1m a year that it would deliver.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Conclusion</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Re</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">garding the proposed residen</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ce </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">est</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">, we</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> believe that the Ministry of Justice has not made the case for this significant change to the administration of legal aid, providing no reasoning, evidence or analysis to support their proposals. There remains a gulf</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> between the proposed residence test and the policy aims it is meant to serve: saving public money or bolstering public confidence in the legal aid system. On saving public funds, the Ministry of Justice not only presents no estimate of the scale of ‘waste</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">’ that it claims exists or, consequently, of the scale of savings it hopes to make. It take</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">s no</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> account of unintended consequences such as the cost of satellite litigation to settle disputes around evidence, or the cost to the courts of numerous litigants </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">in person with no legal help. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Given these significant shortcomings, together with our concerns over the fairness and legality of the residence test, we</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">suggest</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> that this proposal be </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">suspended and </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">fundamentally </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">reconsidered.</span></li><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">The current consultation, ‘Judic</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ial Review: Proposals for Further Reform’, is the third consultation on </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">‘reforming’ </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Judicial Reviews that the Ministry of Justice has conducted over the past year</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> – an indication of the department’s zeal for curtailing access to this important legal </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">check</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> This casts current proposals in a tendentious light. The </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">spurious</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> claim that</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">legal aid pays for ‘too many’ J</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">udicial </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">eview cases without merit</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> is similarly unhelpful: it is known that m</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ost Judicial R</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">eview cases settle before they reach permission stage</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ttracting</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> compromise </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">and settlement shows their strength</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">, not weakness</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Settling</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> ahead of hearing stage saves money for the courts and </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">responding </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">public authorities.</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Furthermore</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">, the </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">current gate keepers of the supposedly ‘broken’ system of legal aid funding for Judicial Reviews are the </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">Legal Aid Agency</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">he Ministry of Justice has itself to blame for </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">failing to filter out</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> cases of </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">insufficient</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> merit and should seek to correct its deci</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">sion making </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">processes</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> first.</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">In light of this, as well as the concerns we have over legality and access to effective redress, we</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">suggest</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> that this proposal be suspended and </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">fundamentally </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">reconsidere</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">We consider it outrageous that proposals with such prof</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">ound and far-reaching constitutional implications as limitations on access to Judicial Review be merely nodded through as Statutory Instruments, without so much as a parliamentary debate. We </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">believe that </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">parliament should </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">preserve</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> its role as legislator</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt"> an</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">d its scrutiny over the executive</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">, and w</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">e urge </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">House of Lords Constitution Committee to launch its own inquiry into the proposals to curtail legal aid for Judicial Review</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">, and possibly for the residence test as well</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">27 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:9pt">Written Evidence from Law Centres Network - Page </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold">5</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:9pt"> of </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold">5</span></p></div></body></html>